Summary of Development Team Project: Project Report


Our team project applied machine learning techniques to the Airbnb-NYC-2019 dataset to investigate whether Airbnb can identify pricing patterns and listing segments that support hosts in setting competitive prices. Following the CRISP-DM methodology, we performed exploratory data analysis, data cleaning, feature engineering, and model development to ensure reliable analysis.

We developed and compared three regression models to predict listing prices and found that the polynomial regression model achieved the best performance, explaining approximately 54% of the variation in listing prices. The analysis identified room type as the strongest pricing factor, followed by borough location, availability, and review-related features. We also implemented K-Means clustering, identifying three distinct listing segments—entire homes, private rooms, and shared rooms—which provide practical guidance for pricing and market positioning.

Based on our findings, we recommended that Airbnb adopt data-driven pricing benchmarks, provide segment-specific guidance for hosts, improve the interpretation of listing availability, and explore growth opportunities in underrepresented boroughs. Overall, the project demonstrated how machine learning can support strategic decision-making in the short-term rental market while highlighting the limitations of using historical listing data without customer behaviour or seasonal information.
